ce:section.ce:para:
The SSF cl-CDs were further utilized as the fluorescent colouring agent to develop latent fingerprint. Fig. 4
                        a shows the schematic representation of cl-CDs used as fluorescent dusting powder for latent fingerprint development. Fig. 4b shows a developed fingerprint of an adult realized with the aid of cl-CDs. The magnified images of the identified features are shown in Fig. 4b (1–9). The figure clearly reveals the all minute features such as ridge ending, bifurcation, bridge, island/short ridge, double bifurcation, pores eye/enclosure, incipient ridges, and line unit. Fig. S6a shows the gray level intensity profile of the latent fingerprint image and the gray level intensity profile directly detects fingerprint features by scanning the ridge lines on the gray level image. Fig. 4c shows the gray scale intensity profile corresponding to the fingerprint image identified on a chart paper substrate which is presented in the inset. Further, to increase the material's range of potential applications, latent fingerprint imaging was further performed on different substrates (glass, iron, steel, glossy paper, and plastic), and corresponding gray level intensity profiles were plotted (Fig. S7b – h). As shown in Figure, the gray level intensity profiles are clear with varying gray values across the image and show ridges and furrows clearly which suggests the successful exploration of cl-CDs as a labelling agent to visualize latent fingerprints on diverse surfaces. Additionally, the biocompatibility of cl-CDs was analyzed in the L929 (Mouse fibroblast) cell line using MTT assay. Results indicate that cl-CDs are a safer option for fingerprint imaging compared to commercially available fingerprint powders (Table 1
                        ).
